Question 1

To examine the percentage of tournaments that schools have won, first I filtered the wncaa dataset for observations where tourney_finish equals Champ.

champs <- wncaa |> 
  filter(tourney_finish == "Champ")

Now I will calculate the percentage of tournaments each team has.

percent_wins <- champs |> 
  group_by(school) |> 
  summarise(N = n()) |> 
  mutate(percent = N / sum(N), 
         pct = round((percent*100), 0))

       mapping = aes(x = school,

  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 100)) +
  coord_flip() + 
  labs(title = "Percentage of Tournaments won by school", x = "School", y = "Tournament Win Percentage (%)", caption = "source: WNCAA")

The patterns that I see are that most schools have around 2-6% of tournaments won, with only 2 high outliers. The 2 teams that have won the most are UConn and Tennessee.

Question 2

champ_names <- unique(champs$school)
winners <- wncaa %>% 
  filter(school %in% champ_names)
ggplot(winners, 
       mapping = aes(x = school, 
                     y = seed, 
                     fill = school)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.2) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Seeds by School", x = "School", y = "Seed", caption = "source: WNCAA")

After making boxplots showing the distribution of seeds by school for schools who have won a championship before, I will reorder the distributions in an order that is easier to understand. I will do this by ordering it from highest average seed to lowest average seed.

winners <- winners |>   
  group_by(school) %>%  
  mutate(mean_seed = mean(seed)) %>% 
  ungroup()
ggplot(winners, 
       aes(x = reorder(school, -mean_seed), y = seed, fill = school)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Seeds by School", x = "School", y = "Seed", caption = "source: WNCAA")

From this reordered graph from least to greatest average seed (lower seed meaning the team is ranked as better than the higher seeds) I can see that the IQR of seeds tends to increase as the average seed increases. Many schools have a few high outliers when they were ranked very high. It makes sense that Tennessee and UConn have very little variability and center around a seed of 1 because they have the most championships. No big surprises.

Now I will try to make the same graph as above but with geom_violin() instead of geom_boxplot().

ggplot(winners, 
       aes(x = reorder(school, -mean_seed), y = seed, fill = school)) +
  geom_violin() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Seeds by School", x = "School", y = "Seed", caption = "source: WNCAA")

The graph with boxplots is more informative because you can directly see the median and IQR and which points are outliers, while with geom_violin it is less clear where these locations are. Although, the violin graph is much more appealing, the boxplots graph provides more information as it is easier to see the individual locations and data points. It is also easier to differentiate between distributions, since some schools on the violin graph have very similar distributions.

Question 4

winners_mean_sd <- winners |> 
  group_by(school) |> 
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric),
                   list(mean = mean,
                        sd = sd)))

Now we will explore the average win percentage of these schools across the seasons with this new dataset called winners_mean_sd.

ggplot(winners_mean_sd,
        mapping = aes(x = reorder(school, reg_percent_mean, na.rm = TRUE),
                      y = reg_percent_mean)) +
  geom_point() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Regular Season Win Percentage by School", x = "School", y = "Average Regular Season Win Percentage", caption = "source: WNCAA")

From the graph, I can see that the tournament winner who had the lowest regular season win percentage was Texas A&M with 73.98667%. There is a wide spread of regular season win percentages with most schools ranging from 75% to 87%, with one high outlier of 91.53667% which is UConn. There is also a cluster of schools that have a regular season win percentage between 77.5% and 80%.

Now I will try to take into account the standard deviation in the graph.

ggplot(winners_mean_sd,
        mapping = aes(x = reorder(school, reg_percent_mean, na.rm = TRUE),
                      y = reg_percent_mean)) +
  geom_pointrange(mapping = aes(ymin = reg_percent_mean - reg_percent_sd,
       ymax = reg_percent_mean + reg_percent_sd)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Regular Season Win Percentage by School", x = "School", y = "Average Regular Season Win Percentage", caption = "source: WNCAA")

The school with the narrowest interval is Texas A&M. This means that Texas A&M has the least variation in regular season win percentage among these tournament winning schools. In other words, the regular season win percentage for Texas A&M varies less by season compared to other schools, typically ranging from around 67.5% to 79%.

ggplot(winners_mean_sd,
        mapping = aes(x = reorder(school, reg_percent_mean, na.rm = TRUE),
                      y = reg_percent_mean)) +
  geom_linerange(mapping = aes(ymin = reg_percent_mean - reg_percent_sd,
       ymax = reg_percent_mean + reg_percent_sd)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Regular Season Win Percentage by School", x = "School", y = "Average Regular Season Win Percentage", caption = "source: WNCAA")

Yes, I can make the same graph using geom_linerange() but it is not a great idea because although you can still see the variability in regular season win percentage for each school from 1 standard deviation below to 1 standard deviation above the mean, you cannot actually see where the mean regular season win percentage is on the graph.
